==English==

===Etymology===
{{etyl|la}}, a form of {{term|pugno|pugnō|I fight|lang=la}}, from {{term|pugnus||fist|lang=la}}, from {{proto|Indo-European}} roots.

===Pronunciation===
*: {{rhymes|eɪʃəs}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# Naturally [[aggressive]] or [[hostile]]; [[combative]]; [[belligerent]].
#* '''1858''', [[w:Anthony Trollope|Anthony Trollope]], ''Dr Thorne'', ch. 3:
#*: Not that the doctor was a bully, or even '''pugnacious''', in the usual sense of the word; he had no disposition to provoke a fight, no propense love of quarrelling.
#* '''1904''', [[w:Jack London|Jack London]], ''The Sea Wolf'', ch. 15:
#*: As he made the demand he spat out a mouthful of blood and teeth and shoved his '''pugnacious''' face close to Oofty-Oofty.
#* '''2003''', [[w:Ken Follett|Ken Follett]], ''Hornet Flight'', ISBN 9780451210746, [http://books.google.ca/books?id=cveoqrRNew0C&dq=pugnacious+subject%3A%22fiction%22&q=pugnacious#v=snippet&q=pugnacious&f=false pp. 249-250]:
#*: In the face of bad news Churchill normally became even more '''pugnacious''', always wanting to respond to defeat by going on the attack.

